  <assign id="1141">
    <name>Practice Anticipating Responses and Preparing to Monitor</name>
    <intro>&lt;p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"&gt;Let’s revisit the &lt;em&gt;Identifying Similar Triangles&lt;/em&gt; task from Session 5.5. (The teacher guide for the full lesson can be downloaded at&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://www.map.mathshell.org/lessons.php?unit=8320&amp;amp;collection=8" target="_blank" title="Mathematics Assessment Project website - opens in a new window"&gt;https://www.map.mathshell.org/lessons.php?unit=8320&amp;amp;collection=8&lt;/a&gt;.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"&gt;For this activity, imagine that you are planning to use this task (from&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Sorting Triangles&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;Card D) with your learners: Are triangles &lt;em&gt;PQR&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;STR&lt;/em&gt; similar?&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p dir="ltr" style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/SortingTriangles_CardD.png" alt="Triangle PQR has angle Q labeled 70 degrees. Segment ST, parallel to side PQ, cuts across Triangle PQR to form Triangle STR." class="img-responsive atto_image_button_text-bottom" width="500" height="364"&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p dir="ltr" style="text-align: center;"&gt;Used with permission from the &lt;a href="https://www.map.mathshell.org/" target="_blank" title="Mathematics Assessment Project website - opens in a new window"&gt;Mathematics Assessment Project&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Do the math of the activity and &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;anticipate&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; student responses, including correct, incomplete, and incorrect responses you may see from students you know.&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;For each anticipated response, write at least one probing question you might ask a student about the response as you &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;monitor&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; as students work. Label the question based on the types of questions described below. The type of
        question might be:
        &lt;ul style="padding-top: 10px"&gt;
            &lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Visible&lt;/em&gt;—The probing question might encourage the student to make a specific part of their work more visible. &lt;br&gt;Example: “What might it look like to . . . ?”&lt;/li&gt;
            &lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Deeply&lt;/em&gt;—The probing question might encourage the student to think more deeply about the problem. &lt;br&gt;Example: “What if &lt;em&gt;ST&lt;/em&gt; were in a different place inside the triangle, but still parallel to &lt;em&gt;PQ&lt;/em&gt;? How would your argument
                change?”
                &lt;br&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
            &lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Misconception&lt;/em&gt;—The probing question might encourage the student to notice and address a misconception in their work. &lt;br&gt;Example: “I’m wondering about your claim that . . . What is true about parallel lines that you might use here?”&lt;br&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;/ul&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Instructions for submitting the assignment:&lt;/strong&gt; Click the ADD SUBMISSION button below. You may then upload a document, photos, or video of your work. You may choose to respond to #1 and #2 separately or incorporate your response to #1 in
    the monitoring sheet you create for #2. Click SAVE CHANGES to save your work. Click SUBMIT ASSIGNMENT when you are done.&lt;/p&gt;</intro>
